  childSummary:"When you open Instagram or YouTube, you DON'T see posts in the order they were posted — a computer picks what to show you! It looks at: what you liked before, what you watched for a long time, what your friends liked, and what's popular right now. Then it gives each post a SCORE — 'how likely is this person to like/watch/share this?' — and shows you the highest-scoring content first. That's why your Instagram looks completely different from your friend's — the computer creates a unique feed just for YOU. The goal? Keep you scrolling as long as possible, because the longer you stay, the more ads you see, and that's how these free apps make money!",
